article.headline: Wyoming 69, San Diego State 65
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Jay Straight is playing for the present and the future. After leading Wyoming over San Diego State 69-65 Monday night, the senior guard said he wants to keep the season going and at the same time set an example for the underclassmen on the team. "I'm just trying to pass the torch ... to the young guys in this program," Straight said. Straight put the torch to the Aztecs, scoring 18 points, including two free throws with 20 seconds left, as the Cowboys (15-10 overall, 7-5 Mountain West Conference) snapped a two-game losing streak and handed SDSU its third straight loss. Straight, who also had six assists to tie the conference's career assist mark of 439, sank his free throws after Trimaine Davis pulled the Aztecs to within 65-63 with two foul shots of his own with 51 seconds remaining. Brandon Heath, who led SDSU with 14 points, scored with 4 seconds to go, but Wyoming's Dion Sherrell finished off the Aztecs with two more free throws a second later. For the game, Straight hit all six of his free throw attempts and Sherrell all five of his. As a team, Wyoming made 21 of 23 foul shots. "We made our free throws tonight and that was the difference in the game," Wyoming coach Steve McClain said, crediting the leadership of his senior players. "This senior class really has stepped up this season," he said. "After we lost to Utah a month ago, from that point forward our seniors have really led this team well. For a team that was picked to finish last in the conference, we're still just a half game out of second place." The Cowboys, who led 35-26 at the half, also got 12 points from reserve Kevin Lewis, who entered the game averaging 4.6 points, 11 from Sherrell and 10 from Justin Williams. Davis, John Sharper and Matt Thomas added 11 each for SDSU (10-14, 4-7), which lost its two previous games in overtime. "We are playing people close, we are competing, we are fighting hard, but we have to find a way to make a play when you have a chance to win," SDSU coach Steve Fisher said. Wyoming plays next at Colorado State on Saturday night. "I wish we were playing there tomorrow," an upbeat Straight said. With just two games left in the regular season before the league tournament, McClain is telling his players to take one game at a time. "I've told our kids that we don't need to worry about what the other teams in the league are doing," he said. "We just need to take care of ourselves."
